{"parse":{"title":"Lehr (glassmaking)","pageid":14286576,"revid":814691398,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>lehr</b> is a temperature-controlled <a href=\"/wiki/Kiln\" title=\"Kiln\">kiln</a> for <a href=\"/wiki/Annealing_(glass)\" title=\"Annealing (glass)\">annealing</a> objects made of <a href=\"/wiki/Glass\" title=\"Glass\">glass</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McLellan_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McLellan-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The resulting objects have less internal <a href=\"/wiki/Stress_(physics)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Stress (physics)\">stress</a> and thus are less prone to breaking.\n</p><p>Rapid cooling of molten glass generates an uneven temperature distribution in the body of the glass, which results in mechanical stress sufficient to cause cracking before the object has reached ambient temperature, or to result in susceptibility to cracking in later use, often triggered by <a href=\"/wiki/Thermal_shock\" title=\"Thermal shock\">thermal shock</a>. To prevent this, objects manufactured from molten glass are annealed by cooling gradually in a lehr from a temperature just below the solidification point of the glass. Anneal cooling rate depends on the thickness of the glass and can range from several tens of degrees Celsius per hour for thin sections to a fraction of a degree Celsius per hour for thick slabs or castings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-bullseye_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bullseye-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-McLellan_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McLellan-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In glass manufacture, a lehr is typically a long kiln with a temperature <a href=\"/wiki/Gradient\" title=\"Gradient\">gradient</a> from end to end, through which newly made glass objects such as glasses or vases are transported on a <a href=\"/wiki/Conveyor_belt\" title=\"Conveyor belt\">conveyor belt</a>.  However, the same effect can be obtained in a small kiln by controlling the cooling rate with an electronic temperature controller.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lehr_(glassmaking)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-McLellan-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-McLellan_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McLellan_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">GW McLellan and EB Shand (1984), Glass Engineering Handbook, 3rd Edition, New York, McGraw Hill. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-07-044823-X\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-07-044823-X\">0-07-044823-X</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-07-044823-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-07-044823-0\">978-0-07-044823-0</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-bullseye-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-bullseye_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.bullseyeglass.com/methods-ideas/annealing-thick-slabs.html\">\"Annealing Thick Slabs\"</a>. <i>Kilncasting</i>. June 15, 2009.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Kilncasting&amp;rft.atitle=Annealing+Thick+Slabs&amp;rft.date=2009-06-15&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bullseyeglass.com%2Fmethods-ideas%2Fannealing-thick-slabs.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALehr+%28glassmaki